\"status\":\"pending\",\"user_feedback\":null,\"user_pattern\":0,\"effort\":7,\"impact\":9,\"implemented_at\":null,\"created_at\":\"2026-03-18T11:56:35.134Z\",\"updated_at\":\"2026-03-18T11:56:35.134Z\",\"requirement_id\":null,\"goal_id\":null,\"risk\":8,\"provider\":null,\"model\":null,\"detailed\":0}}","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b399cdad-908a-4da4-833a-66507675ad51","uuid":"33b75ad5-de69-4fcd-805f-9a2ce91c5076","timestamp":"2026-03-18T11:56:35.154Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"{\"idea\":{\"id\":\"7ee5ae64-329d-4e9f-8b2b-d445c5768ec5\",\"scan_id\":\"52ba2374-c265-4bef-9bba-7af5aa7cdd4a\",\"project_id\":\"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\"context_id\":null,\"scan_type\":\"tech_innovator\",\"category\":\"performance\",\"title\":\"OS keystore-backed master key with DPAPI/Keychain\",\"description\":\"Move the master encryption key out of the MASTER_KEY environment variable and into the OS-level secure keystore (Windows DPAPI, macOS Keychain, Linux kernel keyring). The master key would be sealed at rest and only unwrapped into process memory during derivation calls, with the plaintext buffer zeroed immediately after use. TenantKeyManager already zeros cached key buffers (line 126-129) but the master secret itself sits in a plain string for the entire process lifetime. Proof-of-concept: use node-keytar or the native crypto.subtle API to store/retrieve the master secret from the OS keystore, measure derivation latency overhead, and verify the key never appears in a core dump or /proc/pid/environ. Risk: adds a native dependency; deployment environments (Docker) may lack keystore access requiring a fallback path; key provisioning workflow changes significantly.\",\"reasoning\":\"The master secret is loaded from an environment variable (config.ts:55) and held as a plain string in TenantKeyManager for the entire process lifetime. Any memory dump, core file, or /proc access exposes every tenant key. This is the weakest link in an otherwise well-structured encryption chain � the system has proper AES-256-GCM, per-tenant key derivation, and buffer zeroing, but the root of trust is a plaintext string. Moving to OS keystore integration makes key extraction from a compromised process orders of magnitude harder and is a prerequisite for serious compliance certification (SOC2, HIPAA).\",\"status\":\"pending\",\"user_feedback\":null,\"user_pattern\":0,\"effort\":7,\"impact\":9,\"implemented_at\":null,\"created_at\":\"2026-03-18T11:56:35.134Z\",\"updated_at\":\"2026-03-18T11:56:35.134Z\",\"requirement_id\":null,\"goal_id\":null,\"risk\":8,\"provider\":null,\"model\":null,\"detailed\":0}}","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
[2026-03-18T11:56:36.608Z] [STDOUT] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Np5WS8Sq2iuUeUAcTXXs4Z","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01BPu6Vk2PqWra9kVeW5Z5Jb","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/ideas \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\n    \"scan_id\": \"52ba2374-c265-4bef-9bba-7af5aa7cdd4a\",\n    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n    \"scan_type\": \"tech_innovator\",\n    \"category\": \"functionality\",\n    \"title\": \"Isolated credential vault with sealed storage\",\n    \"description\": \"Extract all credential storage from the per-tenant SQLite databases into a dedicated, independently encrypted credential vault. Currently persona_credentials lives in the same database as personas, events, and executions (schema.ts:101-113), meaning database backups, replication, and access patterns for secrets are identical to application data. The vault would be a separate SQLite database per tenant with its own encryption-at-rest (SQLCipher or application-level page encryption), independent backup schedule, and a narrow access API that enforces decrypt-on-read with mandatory audit logging. Proof-of-concept: create a CredentialVault class that opens a separate SQLite file for credentials, migrates existing credential rows from the tenant DB, and exposes get/put methods that integrate with TenantKeyManager. Verify that application DB backups no longer contain encrypted credential data. Risk: doubles the number of SQLite connections per tenant; cross-database foreign keys (persona_credential_links) need to become application-enforced; migration must be atomic to prevent credential loss.\",\n    \"reasoning\": \"Credentials sharing a database with application data (schema.ts:101-113) means any database leak, unprotected backup, or SQL injection that reads from the tenant DB also exposes encrypted credential ciphertext. While the ciphertext is AES-256-GCM encrypted, defense-in-depth demands the ciphertext itself not be co-located with application data. Separating the credential store creates an independent security boundary — you can apply different retention, backup, access, and audit policies to secrets vs. application data. This architectural separation compounds: every future compliance requirement, audit capability, or access control improvement applies cleanly to the vault without touching the application schema.\",\n    \"effort\": 9,\n    \"impact\": 9,\n    \"risk\": 8\n  }'","description":"Save idea 4: isolated credential vault"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1145,"cache_read_input_tokens":55148,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1145},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b399cdad-908a-4da4-833a-66507675ad51","uuid":"dfc70d49-cc1e-4735-ad4d-4da910c9727d"}
